    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Built in 1852 to shelter the orange trees of the Tuileries Garden in winter, the Orangerie was transformed into a museum after World War I at the direct request of Claude Monet. The centrepiece is <strong>Les Nymphéas</strong> — eight monumental Water Lilies murals painted over three decades and installed in two purpose-built oval rooms with natural overhead light, exactly as Monet designed. The paintings wrap 360 degrees around the viewer. The rooms were restored to their original skylighted form during a major renovation completed in 2006, returning the natural daylight Monet had specified.</p>
    <p>The lower level houses the <strong>Walter-Guillaume collection</strong> — 144 works assembled by art dealer Paul Guillaume and his wife Domenica, covering the first decades of the 20th century. Works by Renoir, Cézanne, Matisse, Picasso, Modigliani, Soutine, and Derain form one of the most coherent private collections of the Modernist period. The museum is smaller than the Musée d'Orsay and significantly less crowded, though timed entry is mandatory for all visitors. The museum also hosts a temporary exhibition programme — check musee-orangerie.fr for the current season.</p>
    <p>All visitors must book a timed entry slot at billetterie.musee-orangerie.fr before arriving — this applies equally to those entitled to free admission. The museum officially warns against resellers, mirror booking sites, and street vendors. Reseller tickets have been refused at the door. Photography is not permitted anywhere inside the museum. The entrance is at the western edge of the Jardin des Tuileries, on the Seine side of Place de la Concorde, accessible from Métro Concorde (lines 1, 8, 12).<br/><br/>Last updated: March 2026 · Verified</p>
