  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div class="sec">
    <div class="sec-t">FAQ</div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">How much does Musée de l'Orangerie cost?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Full price is €12.50. Reduced tickets (€9.50) are available for non-EU visitors under 26, students, and people with disabilities. Entry is free for EU citizens under 26, all visitors under 18, and all visitors on the first Sunday of each month — a free timed reservation is still required. On Fridays during exhibition periods the evening rate from 18:00 is €10. Book at billetterie.musee-orangerie.fr.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What are the opening hours and which day is it closed?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Open Monday and Wednesday to Sunday, 9:00–18:00. On Fridays during exhibition periods the museum stays open until 21:00 (last entry 20:15, galleries close 20:45). Closed every Tuesday, 25 December, 1 May, and the morning of 14 July. Rooms begin closing 30 minutes before the museum's closing time.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Do I need to book in advance — and why avoid resellers?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Yes — all visitors must book a timed entry slot, including those entitled to free admission. Book exclusively at billetterie.musee-orangerie.fr. The museum officially warns against "skip-the-line" ticket sites, mirror websites, and street vendors — reseller tickets risk being refused at the door. The official site is available in English and charges no markup.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">Can I take photos inside the Musée de l'Orangerie?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">Photography is not permitted inside the museum. This applies to all rooms including the oval Water Lilies rooms. The restriction is enforced by staff throughout the visit.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fq">
      <div class="fq-q">What is in the Musée de l'Orangerie besides the Water Lilies?</div>
      <div class="fq-a">The lower level houses the Walter-Guillaume collection — 144 works assembled by dealer Paul Guillaume and his wife Domenica, including major works by Renoir, Cézanne, Matisse, Picasso, Modigliani, Soutine, and Derain. The museum also runs temporary exhibitions — check musee-orangerie.fr for the current programme.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

